  "prompt": "What is the history of people immigrating to Australia from China, Japan, and Korea?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of immigration from China, Japan, and Korea to Australia:\n\nChinese Immigration:\n- First significant Chinese migration began during the 1850s Gold Rush\n- Many Chinese came as miners during the gold rush period\n- Faced significant discrimination, including the White Australia Policy (1901-1973)\n- Restricted immigration until the 1970s\n- Post-1980s saw increased immigration, particularly skilled professionals and students\n- Now one of the largest immigrant groups in Australia\n\nJapanese Immigration:\n- Limited immigration until after World War II\n- Initially mostly businesspeople and students\n- Increased significantly in the 1970s and 1980s\n- Many came for economic opportunities and cultural exchange\n- Significant number of Japanese residents in major cities like Sydney and Melbourne\n- Strong economic and cultural ties between Japan and Australia\n\nKorean Immigration:\n- Relatively recent compared to Chinese immigration\n- Significant increase after the 1970s\n- Many came as students, professionals, and skilled workers\n- Immigration grew substantially in the 1990s and 2000s\n- Concentrated in major urban areas\n- Many involved in business, technology, and education sectors\n\nAll three groups have experienced varying levels of integration and faced different challenges in Australian society, with immigration policies becoming more inclusive since the 1970s.",
